  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks in different regions:\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- European Union: AML Directives\n- United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n- International standards set by Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n\n3. Typical requirements:\n- Customer due diligence\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting large or suspicious transactions\n- Implementation of risk-based compliance programs\n\nThese regulations apply to banks, credit unions, money transfer services, cryptocurrency exchanges, and other financial institutions. Penalties for non-compliance can include significant fines and potential criminal charges.",
